    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i get the feathering part, but what about when i'm doing the corners? the bathroom has some tight angles and i'm worried about the mud cracking in the corners once it dries. how do i prevent that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Corners, those tricky little nooks and crannies! They're where the little shadows hide, and if you mess up the corner, you've got a whole patch of exposed, ugly dirt waiting to happen. Don't be a fool and try to just shove mud into the corner like a clumsy goblin trying to squeeze into a tiny hole.\n\nFor corners, you need to use a specific technique. Instead of just pushing mud in, you want to build up the corner gradually, like stacking tiny, perfectly shaped pebbles. Start by applying a thin layer of compound right into the corner, making sure it flows smoothly into the adjacent flat surfaces.\n\nThen, use your taping knife—and I mean *really* use that knife—to pull that mud out and smooth it over. You are essentially sculpting the corner. Think of it like carving a tiny, neat little cave entrance. If you let it dry too fast, those little stress points will pop up, and you'll have cracks that look like tiny, angry spiderwebs.\n\nA good trick is to let those initial coats dry *just* enough so they hold their shape, but not so long that they become rock-hard. Then, you go back with a lighter",
      "source": "target",
